## Audit Plan
1. Static Analysis: check semantic elements, roles, and ARIA usage on nav structure
2. Keyboard Flow: check focusability and keyboard operability of all interactive elements
3. AT Simulation: check announced name, role, state for all interactive elements
4. Focus Management: check dropdown expand/collapse focus behavior

## Findings

### Finding 1: Non-semantic Dropdown Trigger (Severity: Critical)
**WCAG Reference**: 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value (Level AA) | Section 508 §502.3.3
**Observation**: The "Products" dropdown trigger is implemented as a `div` with an
  `onclick` handler. `div` elements carry no implicit ARIA role, are not in the
  tab order by default, and expose no state (`aria-expanded`) to assistive technologies.
**User Impact**: Keyboard-only users cannot reach or activate the Products dropdown at all —
  the `div` is skipped entirely during Tab navigation. Screen reader users (JAWS, NVDA,
  VoiceOver) receive no announcement that this item is interactive or that it controls
  a submenu, leaving the entire Products section inaccessible.
**Why it works**: A native `button` element carries an implicit `role="button"`, is
  natively keyboard-focusable, and fires on both Enter and Space — eliminating the need
  for manual keyboard handlers. `aria-expanded` communicates open/closed state to AT.

**Remediation**:
```html
<!-- Before -->
<div onclick="showDropdown()">Products</div>

<!-- After -->
<button type="button"
        aria-expanded="false"
        aria-controls="dropdown"
        onclick="toggleDropdown(this)">
  Products
</button>
```
```javascript
// JavaScript: update aria-expanded on toggle
function toggleDropdown(btn) {
  const expanded = btn.getAttribute('aria-expanded') === 'true';
  btn.setAttribute('aria-expanded', String(!expanded));
  document.getElementById(btn.getAttribute('aria-controls'))
    .style.display = expanded ? 'none' : 'block';
}
```

### Finding 2: Dropdown Items Hidden from AT When Closed (Severity: Major)
**WCAG Reference**: 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value (Level AA); 2.1.1 Keyboard (Level A)
**Observation**: The dropdown `ul` is hidden with `display:none`, which correctly
  removes it from AT and keyboard flow when closed. However, there is no focus
  management to move focus into the dropdown when it opens, or back to the trigger
  when it closes. Users who open the dropdown via keyboard are left at an unknown
  position in the tab order.
**User Impact**: Keyboard and screen reader users who open the Products dropdown do not
  know where focus has gone. They must Tab through the rest of the page to discover
  the newly visible items, which is disorienting, particularly for screen reader users
  who rely on announced focus changes to understand context.

**Remediation**:
```javascript
// Move focus to first dropdown item on open
function toggleDropdown(btn) {
  const expanded = btn.getAttribute('aria-expanded') === 'true';
  const dropdown = document.getElementById(btn.getAttribute('aria-controls'));
  btn.setAttribute('aria-expanded', String(!expanded));
  dropdown.style.display = expanded ? 'none' : 'block';
  if (!expanded) {
    // Move focus to first link in dropdown
    const firstLink = dropdown.querySelector('a');
    if (firstLink) firstLink.focus();
  }
}
// On Escape, close dropdown and return focus to trigger
document.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {
  if (e.key === 'Escape') {
    const trigger = document.querySelector('[aria-expanded="true"]');
    if (trigger) {
      trigger.setAttribute('aria-expanded', 'false');
      document.getElementById(trigger.getAttribute('aria-controls'))
        .style.display = 'none';
      trigger.focus();
    }
  }
});
```

## Verification Summary
All 4 audit plan steps executed.
Findings: 2 Critical=1, Major=1.
WCAG 4.1.2 (Robust) — verified correct. WCAG 2.1.1 (Operable) — verified correct.
Section 508 §502.3.3 — verified maps to 4.1.2. All criterion numbers confirmed. ✓
